*header: Debate Interpretation Project
*header: Participant Information Sheet

*What is the purpose of this project? What will happen if I agree to take part?*

The purpose of this project is to learn more about how people judge debates on challenging topics. We hope that having a better understanding of this will allow AI developers to better develop 'scalable oversight' techniques that allow us to be more justifiably confident in AI systems' answers to challenging questions, and which could reduce certain risks associated with the development and deployment of AI systems.

If you agree to take part, you will be asked to answer some initial questions. The questions about your level of education, as well as your level of experience with physics and computer programming, are required. You may answer "prefer not to say" to any of the other "details about yourself" questions, although we appreciate your answers where you are happy to provide them.

You will then be asked to analyse a debate; you will receive more specific details when you reach this part of the study. Note that we expect that the question being debated may be challenging, and we do not necessarily expect or require you to reach the correct conclusion. We are more interested in getting a clear sense of how you reason about the problem. 

We expect the study to take approximately 60 minutes to complete, and you will be paid for your time at the amount specified on the Prolific invitation you responded to.

*What are the risks and benefits of taking part?*

There are no direct benefits to you from taking part other than the payment you will receive. We hope that the data you provide will contribute to the responsible development of AI systems.

In any online study there is a small risk of issues caused by technical glitches or human error. If you encounter any problems with your submission or payment, please reach out directly to the researcher through the Prolific messaging platform.

*Do I have to take part?*

No, your participation is entirely voluntary. If you do decide to take part, you can withdraw at any time and without giving a reason.

*Do you collect personal data? Who will process any personal data you collect? What will happen to any personal data I provide you?*

/Purpose and legal basis./ We will ask some optional "details about yourself" questions (e.g., your gender, age range, etc.) in order to better understand the proportion of participants who fall into particular categories. We will also ask about your level of education, as well as your level of experience with physics and computer programming, in order to better understand the experience (or lack of experience) that participants are bringing to the task. This information is used to carry out research under the legitimate interests pursued by Dr Gabriel Recchia. Your answers to these questions will be shared with the lead researcher Dr Gabriel Recchia. 

/Anonymised data./ Anonymised versions of your responses to all questions may appear in publicly available datasets or be shared with other researchers. These will not be publicly associated with any identifier that could be used to identify you individually, and personal data will be /de-linked/. This means that any specific details you may choose to provide - e.g. your educational status, your gender, etc. - will be separated from each other so that your educational status cannot be connected to your gender, age, and so on.

/Data transfer./ Any information that you may choose to share with us will be subject to algorithmic processing and may be transferred, processed, transmitted and stored outside the European Union. For example, data transfers may occur to servers owned by GuidedTrack (the company that makes the survey software you are using now), Dropbox, or Google (companies that offer digital storage).

/Retention period./ The requested information will be retained for seven years unless we are required by law to retain it for a longer period.

/Your rights./ You have the right to request access to your personal data held by Dr Gabriel Recchia, to have it corrected or deleted, to restrict processing, to object to processing, and to obtain and reuse any personal data that Dr Gabriel Recchia holds on you for your own purposes. However, this does not override our obligation to comply with legal requirements, such as fulfilling obligations to avoid violating applicable laws. You may withdraw your consent at any time; if you do, we will delete your personal data from our systems unless required by law to retain it. However, this does not affect the lawfulness of processing carried out based on your consent before its withdrawal. Additionally, if your data has already been shared publicly or incorporated into publicly available datasets by the time you withdraw consent, we may no longer have the ability to retrieve or delete it from those external sources. To exercise your rights, or if you have any questions, please send your request to the researcher using Prolific's messaging system. You have the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority if you believe that your data protection rights have been infringed.

*Contact for further information* 

If you have any questions, you may contact the research lead, Dr Gabriel Recchia, directly using Prolific's messaging system.

