*label: debate_instructions_intro
*header: How the task works (instructions page 1/20)

In this task, you’ll judge a debate between *Debater A* and *Debater B* about a challenging question.

The debate happens over *4 turns*. For each turn, you will:
1) Click a link that opens that turn in a new tab  
2) Read the Key Question, the debaters’ positions, and any additional info provided
3) Give a probability judgment and answer a free-response question
4) Copy the *encoded version* of your answers and paste it back into this study (we'll explain what this means in a moment)

You do *not* need to be an expert in the specific topic of the question. We mainly care about how you reason with what you’re given.

*button: Next

*header: The debaters (instructions page 2/20)

Both debaters are experts on the topic. One is arguing honestly; the other is not. Part of your job is to figure out who is who.

We’d like you to pay most attention to the strength of the debaters’ arguments, as this will be more informative than “surface” features of their language such as expressions of confidence or uncertainty.

These debates are designed to be difficult, and you are not necessarily expected to be able to reach the correct answer, but we would like you to do your best with the information available.

*button: Next

*header: Checking your comprehension

*question: In this task, which of the following are good reasons to favor one debater over another? (Your submission will not be rejected if you get this or other 'Checking your comprehension' questions wrong - they are just to help make sure that you understand what to do.)
	*save: comp1
	A. One of the debaters sounds more confident
	B. One of the debaters sounds less defensive
	C. One of the debaters sounds more like an expert
	D. One of the debaters has stronger arguments
	E. All of the above  
			
*if: comp1 = "D. One of the debaters has stronger arguments"
	Right! Since both of the debaters are experts in the topic, trying to determine who sounds more confident, less defensive, more like an expert, etc. is unlikely to yield useful information.

*if: not comp1 = "D. One of the debaters has stronger arguments"
	We were actually looking for answer D. Since both of the debaters are experts in the topic, trying to determine who sounds more confident, less defensive, more like an expert, etc. is unlikely to yield useful information.
	
*button: Next
	
*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 3/20)

In the debate you’ll be judging, the debaters abide by certain rules. Let’s walk through these now with an example.

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 4/20)

Each debate opens with a Key Question. For example:

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/01_key_question.png

Questions of this kind can sometimes be read in more than one way. The example above, for example, could be interpreted as asking about the physical magnitude of the force, or about the skater's subjective perception of it.

In cases of ambiguity, your task is to identify the answer that matches the interpretation intended by the expert who wrote the question — that is, the answer you would expect to find in a textbook treatment of the topic.

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 5/20)

Each debater then gives their opening statement.

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/02_opening_statement.png

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 6/20)

Next, each debater gets to respond. They can each respond with two claims of their own, like so:

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/03_two_claims.png

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 7/20)

Each debater can choose a maximum of *ONE* statement to fully respond to. This response is their *main objection*. This is indicated visually in two ways:

- The statement that was objected to will include a note under it saying that the opponent registered a *main objection*.
- An arrow will come out of it, pointing to the opponent's response.

As before, each response consists of exactly two new statements.

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/04_two_new_claims.png

*button: Next

*header: Checking your comprehension

*question: Debater A says "All cats are furry." Debater B replies with the following two counterclaims: (1) "I have a cat that isn't furry." (2) "His name is Bill." How many of these counterclaims is Debater A allowed to *fully respond to*?
	*save: comp2
	A. One of them
	B. Both of them
	C. Neither of them

*if: comp2 = "A. One of them"
	Right! Each debater can choose a maximum of *ONE* of any two statements in a pair to respond directly to.

*if: not comp2 = "A. One of them"
	We were actually looking for answer A. Each debater can choose a maximum of *ONE* of any two statements in a pair to respond directly to.

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 8/20)

Even though debaters can only lodge one main objection to their opponent's two statements, they can also indicate whether or not they fully agree with their opponent's other statement.

If they do, this will appear as a note that they "*fully agree*".
If not, this will appear as a "*secondary objection*".

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/05_secondary_objection.png

Registering a secondary objection is like saying, "For the record, I do not fully agree, even though the rules of the debate do not give me space to explain why."

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 9/20)

In some cases, a debater might agree with both of her opponent's claims, but disagree that these claims refute her own claim.

Alternatively, a debater might disagree with one or both of his opponent's claims, but want to argue that even if these claims were true, they would not refute his own argument.

In such cases, a debater can save their main objection for the idea that the presented claims refute their argument, and any agreements will be described as "agrees but thinks this omits key info".

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/06_omits_key_info.png

*button: Next

*header: The rules of the debate (instructions page 10/20)

*Why would the debaters ever agree on anything, given that they are opponents?*

There are various reasons this can happen:

- If Dishonest makes a claim that is *completely true*, Honest will express agreement with it. This is because Honest is honest, and will therefore agree with true facts.
- The debaters have access to a hidden set of *references* that they can reveal to judges under certain circumstances. If Dishonest knows that Honest has access to a reference that would prove one of Honest's claims is true, then it's in Dishonest's interest to agree with that claim, so that Dishonest isn't caught out in a lie.

You can safely treat *any claim which both debaters agree* on as an established *true fact*.

*button: Next

*header: References (instructions page 11/20)

Debaters may sometimes cite *references* in the form of *sources* or *definitions*.
For the purposes of judging these debates, sources and definitions cited by debaters can be treated as *true* and *reliable*.

*button: Next

*header: References (instructions page 12/20)

Depending on which debate you receive, sources may or may not have *quotes* attached.

*If a source has no quote attached*, *you can trust that the claim attributed from the source really did come from that particular source*.

If a source *does* have a quote attached, or if the debater is citing a definition, then *you should inspect the quote (or definition) to see if it really supports the claim the debater is using it to make*.

*button: Next

*header: Checking your comprehension

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/07_source_example.png

*question: Given the sources above, what can we conclude if Debater A were to make the following statement? Debater A: "Fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour (F. H. et al.), so a team of fire salamanders wouldn't outperform AFC Wimbledon in the FA Cup."
	*save: comp3
	A. We can trust that F. H. et al. is a reliable source, and that it states that fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour
	B. We can trust that F. H. et al. is a reliable source, and that it states that fire salamanders would lose to AFC Wimbledon in the FA Cup
	C. We can trust that F. H. et al. is a reliable source, but we don't know whether it actually states that fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour.
	D. A and B.
	E. We can't trust that F. H. et al. is a reliable source since we know so little about it.

*if: comp3 = "A. We can trust that F. H. et al. is a reliable source, and that it states that fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour"
	Right! We can trust that any source appearing in the sources list is reliable. Given that there is no quote attached, we can take it on faith that the claim attributed to the source ("Fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour") did indeed come from that source. However, the debater's conclusion that follows isn't explicitly stated in the source, and should be evaluated on its own merits.

*if: not comp3 = "A. We can trust that F. H. et al. is a reliable source, and that it states that fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour"
	We were actually looking for answer A. We can trust that any source appearing in the sources list is reliable. Given that there is no quote attached, we can take it on faith that the claim attributed to the source ("Fire salamanders move only 0.1-0.3 kilometers per hour") did indeed come from that source. However, the debater's conclusion that follows isn't explicitly stated in the source, and should be evaluated on its own merits.

*button: Next

*header: Checking your comprehension

*image: https://moduloresearch.com/debates/prolific_detailed_instructions/08_source_example_2.png

*question: Given the sources above, what can we conclude if Debater A were to make this statement? Debater A: "Skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections (Wikipedia, Fire salamander)."
	*save: comp4
	A. We can trust that the Wikipedia article is accurate and reliable, and that it states that skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections.
	B. We can trust that the Wikipedia quote is accurate and reliable, but we should read it carefully to see whether it sufficiently supports Debater A's claim that skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections.
	C. We shouldn't trust that the quote is accurate and reliable, because it comes from Wikipedia.

*if: comp4 = "B. We can trust that the Wikipedia quote is accurate and reliable, but we should read it carefully to see whether it sufficiently supports Debater A's claim that skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections."
	Right! For the purposes of judging these debates, we can trust that any source appearing in the sources list is reliable. However, the conclusion that Debater A is using the quote to support ("Skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections") does not actually seem to be very well supported by the quote, so we may wish to view Debater A's claim skeptically.

*if: not comp4 = "B. We can trust that the Wikipedia quote is accurate and reliable, but we should read it carefully to see whether it sufficiently supports Debater A's claim that skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections."
	We were actually looking for answer B. For the purposes of judging these debates, we can trust that any source appearing in the sources list is reliable. However, the conclusion that Debater A is using the quote to support ("Skin toxins in fire salamanders are the only thing that protect them from bacterial and fungal infections") does not actually seem to be very well supported by the quote, so we may wish to view Debater A's claim skeptically.

*button: Next

*header: Aspects of the debates that are not informative (instructions page 13/20)

Here are some things that are *not* likely to help you evaluate the debate accurately:

- Whether a debater is "Debater A" or "Debater B": Debates have been randomized so that each debater has an equal probability of being the dishonest debater.
- Whether or not a debater uses technical language, "sounds like an expert", speaks confidently, expresses uncertainty, sounds defensive, and so on: Remember, both debaters are experts. Participants generally do best if they ignore superficial features of tone and language, and instead pay attention to whether the debaters have good arguments.

*button: Next

*header: What to do if the task feels overwhelming (instructions page 14/20)

Remember, these debates are designed to be difficult, and you are not necessarily expected to be able to reach the correct answer. We are just interested in learning about how you reason with the information you are given.

*button: Next

*header: Giving your judgment (instructions page 15/20)

Each debate page will ask you to assign a probability that *Debater A* vs *Debater B* matches what an expert would say.

- If you have *no idea* who is right, set the slider to 50%/50%.
- If you lean one way or the other, move the slider to reflect that (e.g., 40%/60%, 70%/30%, etc.).
- If the question seems ambiguous, do your best to answer the way you think the expert who wrote the question would interpret it.

You'll also be asked to explain *why* you chose the probability that you chose. We'd like you to list *all relevant reasons that come to mind*, with a brief remark on how much weight you gave to each.

*button: Next

*header: Timing (instructions page 16/20)

You will have a maximum time limit for each debate turn:
- *Turn 1:* 9 minutes
- *Turn 2:* 9 minutes
- *Turn 3:* 9 minutes
- *Turn 4:* 9 minutes

You don't need to use all the time, but you should take as much time as you need (within the limit) to be as accurate as you can, and to provide a complete answer to the question provided.

When time runs out, the text box will disappear and you will no longer be able to edit your answer. However, you will still be able to copy your answer from the debate page. If you're worried about time, it can help to type a short draft answer early, then improve it if you have time left.

*button: Next

*header: What you may and may not consult (instructions page 17/20)

To keep the task fair and consistent:

- *Do not* use the internet (Google, Wikipedia, forums, etc.) to help you evaluate the debate.
- *Do not* use any large language model or AI assistant.

*button: Next

*header: If there is too much to read within the time limit (instructions page 18/20)

Depending on the debate you receive, it is possible that you may be given an amount of information that feels simply impossible to read or comprehend in the amount of time given. In such cases, we recommend you do your best to orient yourself to the question and any relevant definitions, scroll down to the debate, and do your best with the information available to you in the time you have.

In case it is useful, in most browsers, you can press Ctrl+F (or Command+F) to search the current webpage for a particular word or phrase.

*button: Next

*header: Don't worry about if debaters are "following the rules" (instructions page 19/20)

Don't worry too much about if debaters seem to be "following the rules" of the debate as previously described. We aren't asking you to evaluate whether the debaters are "playing fair". We just want your judgments of how likely it is you believe each side to be the honest expert debater (vs. the dishonest expert debater), based on the strength of their arguments. 

*button: Next

*header: Watch the demo video (instructions page 20/20)

Before you start Turn 1, please watch the demo video explaining the interface.

[Watch the demo video|https://drive.google.com/file/d/1oc_n-zyMj5A5M9N1oWbKRDwIGys_R8jO/view?usp=sharing]

*question: Did you watch the demo video?
